Surface Water Quality Data¶

Source of data:¶

1.For the below EDA, data is gathered from:https://data.baltimorecity.gov/datasets/surface-water-quality-data-1995-through-present/about¶

Exploratory Data Analysis and Visualization¶

1. Water Quality Trends¶

Investigating the trends in water quality over time.¶

In [21]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))# setting the size of the figure.

# here we are labeling x-axis as 'Year'.
plt.xlabel('Year')

# here we are labeling x-axis as 'Mean Water Quality'.
plt.ylabel('Mean Water Quality')

# here we are Setting the title of the plot as 'Water Quality Trends over Time'
plt.title('Water Quality Trends over Time')

# Here Grouping the water quality data by year and calculate the mean of the 'Result' column for each year
df_yearly = df.groupby(df['datetime'].dt.year).mean()

# Reseting the index to include the year as a column
df_yearly.reset_index(inplace=True)

# Creating a line plot of the water quality trends over time using seaborn
sns.lineplot(x='datetime', y='Result', data=df_yearly)

sns.set_style("darkgrid") # here we are setting the style of plot to "darkgrid".

plot shows the water quality trends over time, with the x-axis representing the years and the y-axis representing the mean water quality for each year. The slight decrease in water quality over the years can be seen by the downward trend in the line. we can see whether the water quality has improved, worsened, or remained stable over time.

# setting the size of the figure.
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))

sns.scatterplot(x='GPS Coordinate West', y='GPS Coordinate North', hue='Result',alpha = 0.9, s=60 ,data=df_station)

# here we are setting the style of plot to "darkgrid".
sns.set_style("darkgrid")

# here we are Setting the title of the plot as 'Water Quality by Location'.
plt.title('Water Quality by Location')

# here we are labeling x-axis as 'GPS Coordinate West'.
plt.xlabel('GPS Coordinate West')

# here we are labeling y-axis as 'GPS Coordinate North'.
plt.ylabel('GPS Coordinate North') 

#x-axis ticks are set to be rotated 45 degrees.
plt.xticks(rotation=45)

plt.show()

From the above scatterplot, the hue represents the water quality result, where darker points represent higher water quality values and lighter points represent lower values. Since there are only a few data points with very high water quality values, those points are darker and the majority of the data points have lower water quality values, making them appear lighter in the plot. This suggests that overall, the water quality in the given locations may not be very high, but there are some exceptions with much better water quality values.

3. Creating a folium map of monitoring stations with average water quality results.¶

In [24]:
import folium

# Creating a map centered on Baltimore, Maryland
map_baltimore = folium.Map(location=[39.2904, -76.6122], zoom_start=10)

# Creating a feature group for the monitoring stations
fg_stations = folium.FeatureGroup(name='Monitoring Stations')

# Adding a marker for each monitoring station
for index, row in df_station.iterrows():
    lat = row['GPS Coordinate North']
    lon = row['GPS Coordinate West']
    station_name = row['Station']
    avg_result = row['Result']
    popup_text = f'Station: {station_name}<br>Average Result: {avg_result:.2f}'
    fg_stations.add_child(folium.Marker(location=[lat, lon], popup=popup_text))

# Adding the feature group to the map
map_baltimore.add_child(fg_stations)

# Adding a layer control to toggle the feature groups
folium.LayerControl().add_to(map_baltimore)

# Displays the map
map_baltimore

5. Monitoring the stations which have the highest and lowest water quality results?¶

In [27]:
# Grouping the df by the Station column, then calculating the mean of the Result column for each group (station), and sorting the values in ascending order. The resulting dataframe is then filtered to drop any rows that contain missing values.
df_by_station = df.groupby('Station')['Result'].mean().sort_values().dropna().reset_index()

# creating a barplot using seaborn, where the x-axis represents the 'Result' and the y-axis represents the 'Station'.
sns.barplot(x='Result', y='Station', data=df_by_station.head(10))

# here we are Setting the title of the plot as 'Top 10 Stations with Highest Average Water Quality Results'.
plt.title('Top 10 Stations with Highest Average Water Quality Results')

# here we are labeling x-axis as 'Result'.
plt.xlabel('Result')

# here we are labeling y-axis as 'station'.
plt.ylabel('Station')# here we are labeling y-axis as 'station'.

plt.show()
In [28]:
# creating a bar plot of the average water quality results for the 10 stations with the lowest average results.
sns.barplot(x='Result', y='Station', data=df_by_station.tail(10))

# here we are Setting the title of the plot as 'Top 10 Stations with Lowest Average Water Quality Results'.
plt.title('Top 10 Stations with Lowest Average Water Quality Results')

# here we are labeling x-axis as 'Result'.
plt.xlabel('Result')

# here we are labeling y-axis as 'station'.
plt.ylabel('Station')

plt.show()

This code groups the data by station and calculates the average water quality result for each station, then generates bar plots of the top 10 stations with the highest and lowest results.

6. Water quality results vary by parameter¶

In [29]:
# Setting the size of the figure to 15 x 15 inches
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 15))

# Setting the style of the plot to 'darkgrid'
sns.set_style("darkgrid")

# Creating a KDE plot of water quality results by parameter, with shading enabled
sns.kdeplot(x='Result', hue='Parameter', data=df.dropna(), shade=True)

# Setting the x-axis limits to focus on the majority of data
plt.xlim(left=-0.2, right=0.40)

# here we are Setting the title of the plot to 'Water Quality Results by Parameter'
plt.title('Water Quality Results by Parameter')

# here we are labeling x-axis as 'Result'.
plt.xlabel('Result')

# here we are labeling x-axis as 'Density'.
plt.ylabel('Density')

# Displaying the plot
plt.show()
  1. The code performes a kernel density estimate (KDE) plot of water quality results by parameter ordered by frequency..
  2. we can see that the distribution of pH values is relatively narrow and centered around 0.15. On the other hand, the distribution of Turbidity values is wider and flatter,which is indicating a higher variance in the results.it also shows there is overlap between the distributions of some parameters, such as Turbidity and Chlorine a, which indicates a relationship between these two parameters.

10.Create a pivot table with parameters on the index and years on the columns¶

# creating a pivot table with the index as 'Parameter', columns as years extracted from the 'datetime' column, and values as the mean 'Result' for each year and parameter combination.
parameter_pivot = pd.pivot_table(df, index='Parameter', columns=df['datetime'].dt.year, values='Result')

11. Water Quality Trends at Different Stations over Time¶

In [38]:
# selecting data from 2000 to 2022
df_selected = df[(df['datetime'] >= '2000-01-01') & (df['datetime'] <= '2022-12-31')]

# calculating average result for each station by year
df_by_station_year = df_selected.groupby(['Station', df_selected['datetime'].dt.year])['Result'].mean().reset_index()

# creating a pivot table to make year as column and station as row
df_pivot = df_by_station_year.pivot(index='Station', columns='datetime', values='Result')

# calculating percent change in result from 2000 to 2022 for each station
df_pivot['change'] = (df_pivot[2022] - df_pivot[2000]) / df_pivot[2000] * 100

# sorting stations by change in result
df_change = df_pivot.sort_values(by='change', ascending=False)

# selecting top 10 stations with highest improvement in water quality
df_top_improve = df_change.nlargest(10, 'change')

# selecting top 10 stations with highest deterioration in water quality
df_top_deteriorate = df_change.nsmallest(10, 'change')

First, we select data from 2000 to 2022 using boolean indexing. Next, we group the data by station and year, and calculate the average result. We pivot the resulting table to make year as column and station as row. We calculate the percent change in result from 2000 to 2022 for each station. A negative percent change indicates a deterioration in water quality. The graph helps identify the stations that have experienced the most significant decline in water quality over the years.

Result From Above Analysis¶

The main goal of this project is to analyse the Surface Water Quality Data.

In this project we used various charts , sorting, aggregation and many other python concepts to get the in depth analysis of this data set, we have asked done some analysis and summarized respectively.

Outcomes :¶

  1. The line plot demonstrates a slight decrease in water quality over the years based on the mean water quality values for each year.
  2. The scatterplot with hue represents water quality results, with darker points indicating higher values and lighter points indicating lower values. Some exceptions with better water quality are observed among the majority of lower values.
  3. The map displays monitoring stations as markers, and when clicked, the markers show the station name and average water quality result at that location.
  4. The bar plots showcase the top 10 stations with the highest and lowest water quality results.
  5. The KDE plot displays the distribution of water quality results by parameter, highlighting the density and potential overlap between parameter distributions.
  6. Bar Plot of Average Result by Parameter: The bar plot illustrates the average water quality results for each parameter, showing the parameters with the highest and lowest average values.
  7. The histogram displays the number of samples for each parameter, indicating the count of samples for different parameter values.
  8. The heatmap represents the trends of water quality parameters over time, with colors indicating average parameter values for each year.
  9. The plot showcases the change in water quality from 2000 to 2022 for the top 10 stations with the highest improvement and deterioration.
